    "narrative": "The primary engine for Ghost Ride the WHIP today is **Corbin Carroll**, who stands as our highest-ranked start with a 70.77 score. Despite the traditional penalty for a lefty-on-lefty matchup against Trevor Rogers, the combination of a 16% park boost and a strong 0.372 xwOBA confirms him as our must-start asset. Meanwhile, **James Wood** (64.69) secures the second spot in our rankings due to the immense utility of his leadoff positioning; his matchup against a mid-tier xERA starter in Mitch Keller allows his speed-based production to remain our primary focus in the hunt for the scarcest category, Stolen Bases.\n\nNavigating the deeper end of our lineup, the optimizer heavily favors the park factors in our hitters facing MacKenzie Gore. Both **Max Muncy** (59.01) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (54.52) benefit significantly from the 10% park boost, which pushes them above the marginal threshold. **Trevor Story** (61.82) also provides a surprisingly strong floor against a neutral matchup, proving to be a stable core piece. We are tempering expectations for **Jose Caballero**, whose high base projection is severely hamstrung by a 19% SP skill penalty against Reid Detmers; while his speed is elite, his efficiency is suppressed by the matchup, leaving him as a start we monitor closely.\n\nThe most difficult decision on today\u2019s card was leaving **Giancarlo Stanton** (47.12) on the bench. While his 47.12 score reflects his raw power potential, he ultimately lost out to **Austin Riley** (54.37) and **Josh Naylor** (61.65), whose steadier profiles and superior lineup spots provided a higher floor for daily Roto efficiency. We are also keeping a sharp eye on the risk profiles for **Seiya Suzuki** (53.09); his score is dragged down by a combination of a tough matchup against Aaron Nola and a specific efficiency drain caused by the opposing team's elite catcher defense. With **Vinnie Pasquantino** and **Zach McKinstry** also held in reserve, we are positioned to pinch-hit if early innings reveal that the projected SP skill penalties were too pessimistic for our starters.",
